                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;If one has an lvalue of a structure type, takes the address of a member, and passes that to a function that uses it as a pointer to the member type, would that be regarded as accessing an object of the member type (legal), or an object of the structure type (forbidden)?  A &lt;i&gt;lot&lt;/i&gt; of code assumes it&apos;s legal to access structures in such fashion, and I think a lot of people would squawk at a rule which was understood as forbidding such actions, but it&apos;s unclear what the exact rules are.  Further, unions and structures are treated the same, but sensible rules for each should be different.&lt;/span&gt;

