                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;@BenVoigt: I don&apos;t think the common initial sequence works unless accesses are done via the union.  See &lt;a href=&quot;http://goo.gl/HGOyoK&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer&quot;&gt;goo.gl/HGOyoK&lt;/a&gt; to see what gcc is doing.  If accessing an lvalue of union type via an lvalue of a member type (not using union-member-access operator) was legal, then &lt;code&gt;wow(&amp;amp;u-&amp;gt;s1,&amp;amp;u-&amp;gt;s2)&lt;/code&gt; would need to be legal even when a pointer is used to modify &lt;code&gt;u&lt;/code&gt;, and that would negate most optimizations that the aliasing rule was designed to facilitate.&lt;/span&gt;

